// The two ensures pin the abstracted-set views of r1 and r2 to the same
// self_@.dom(), so by transitivity those view-sets equal each other. The
// prior attempt tried to push this through an `assert forall|p| ... ==>`
// with an explicit `#[trigger]` annotation, but Verus rejected the
// trigger because the sub-expression `|e: EndPoint| e@` is a lambda
// (triggers cannot contain let/forall/exists/lambda/choose), and warned
// about `==>` not assuming the antecedent inside an `assert forall` body.
//
// Drop the quantifier entirely and state the chain as two plain
// implication-shaped asserts. Each is provable by Verus directly (vacuous
// if either ensures fails; transitivity / set extensionality otherwise),
// and neither needs a trigger because there is no bound variable.

// Step 1: chain by `==` transitivity.
assert(r1@.map_values(|e: EndPoint| e@).to_set() == self_@.dom()
    && r2@.map_values(|e: EndPoint| e@).to_set() == self_@.dom()
    ==> r1@.map_values(|e: EndPoint| e@).to_set()
        == r2@.map_values(|e: EndPoint| e@).to_set());

// Step 2: same fact under `Set::ext_equal` (the `=~=` form). Asserting
// both shapes gives z3 two presentations of the same equality, which
// often shakes loose a missing instantiation on the `to_set()` axioms.
assert(r1@.map_values(|e: EndPoint| e@).to_set() == self_@.dom()
    && r2@.map_values(|e: EndPoint| e@).to_set() == self_@.dom()
    ==> r1@.map_values(|e: EndPoint| e@).to_set()
        =~= r2@.map_values(|e: EndPoint| e@).to_set());

// Step 3: bridge `to_set` and `to_set().map(...)` via the vstd identity
// `Seq::lemma_to_set_map_commutes`, which (when broadcast) lets z3
// rewrite `r_i@.map_values(f).to_set()` as `r_i@.to_set().map(f)`. This
// surfaces the same set under a presentation whose top-level call does
// not contain the lambda inside its outermost trigger position, which
// gives the SMT solver another bite at lining the two ensures up.
broadcast use vstd::seq_lib::Seq::lemma_to_set_map_commutes;

assert(r1@.map_values(|e: EndPoint| e@).to_set() == self_@.dom()
    && r2@.map_values(|e: EndPoint| e@).to_set() == self_@.dom()
    ==> r1@.to_set().map(|e: EndPoint| e@)
        == r2@.to_set().map(|e: EndPoint| e@));

